definition.value: A phosphate-linked oligosaccharide analogue consisting of two 3(4)-O-acetyl-alpha-N-acetyl-D-mannosaminyl residues, joined by a (1->6)-phosphodiester linkage. It is a constituent 2-repeating-unit fragment of Neisseria meningitidis serogroup A capsular polysaccharide (MenA), the structural diagram of which shows hydroxy groups partly acetylated at either positions 3 or 4, along with parts of phosphodiester linkages which are present at both the reducing and non-reducing ends of the disaccharide unit.

A phosphate-linked oligosaccharide analogue consisting of three 3(4)-O-acetyl-alpha-N-acetyl-D-mannosaminyl residues, joined by a (1->6)-phosphodiester linkages. It is a constituent 3-repeating-unit segment of Neisseria meningitidis serogroup A capsular polysaccharide (MenA), the structural diagram of which shows hydroxy groups partly acetylated at either positions 3 or 4, along with parts of phosphodiester linkages which are present at both the reducing and non-reducing ends of the trisaccharide unit.
chondroitin-2,6-sulfate

A phosphate-linked oligosaccharide analogue consisting of four 3(4)-O-acetyl-alpha-N-acetyl-D-mannosaminyl residues, joined by (1->6)-phosphodiester linkages. It is a constituent 4-repeating-unit segment of Neisseria meningitidis serogroup A capsular polysaccharide (MenA), the structural diagram of which shows hydroxy groups partly acetylated at either positions 3 or 4, along with parts of phosphodiester linkages which are present at both the reducing and non-reducing ends of the tetrasaccharide unit.

A phosphate-linked oligosaccharide analogue consisting of five 3(4)-O-acetyl-alpha-N-acetyl-D-mannosaminyl residues, joined by (1->6)-phosphodiester linkages. It is a constituent 5-repeating-unit segment of Neisseria meningitidis serogroup A capsular polysaccharide (MenA), the structural diagram of which shows hydroxy groups partly acetylated at either positions 3 or 4, along with parts of phosphodiester linkages which are present at both the reducing and non-reducing ends of the pentasaccharide unit.

A phosphate-linked oligosaccharide analogue consisting of six 3(4)-O-acetyl-alpha-N-acetyl-D-mannosaminyl residues, joined by (1->6)-phosphodiester linkages. It is a constituent 6-repeating-unit segment of Neisseria meningitidis serogroup A capsular polysaccharide (MenA), the structural diagram of which shows hydroxy groups partly acetylated at either positions 3 or 4, along with parts of phosphodiester linkages which are present at both the reducing and non-reducing ends of the hexasaccharide unit.

A phosphate-linked oligosaccharide analogue consisting of seven 3(4)-O-acetyl-alpha-N-acetyl-D-mannosaminyl residues, joined by (1->6)-phosphodiester linkages. It is a constituent 7-repeating-unit segment of Neisseria meningitidis serogroup A capsular polysaccharide (MenA), the structural diagram of which shows hydroxy groups partly acetylated at either positions 3 or 4, along with parts of phosphodiester linkages which are present at both the reducing and non-reducing ends of the heptaasaccharide unit.

An azaspiro compound that is 1-methoxypiperidine which is fused at position 4 to the 5-position of a 1,5-dihydro-2H-pyrrol-2-one that is substituted at positions 1, 3 and 4 by methyl, 4-chloro-2,6-dimethylphenyl and (ethoxycarbonyl)oxy groups, respectively. It is a proinsecticide developed by Syngenta and used to protect a wide range of crops from some of the most damaging, difficult to control sucking pests such as aphids, whiteflies, Pysllids, armoured scales, soft scales, spider mites, rust mites, and red mites including California red scale, green peach aphid (Myzus persicae), tobacco whitefly etc.

A six-carbon aromatic annulene in which each carbon atom donates one of its two 2p electrons into a delocalised pi system. A toxic, flammable liquid byproduct of coal distillation, it is used as an industrial solvent. Benzene is a carcinogen that also damages bone marrow and the central nervous system.
An alpha-amino-acid residue anion obtained by the addition of 2 AMP residues connected by a 3'->5' phosphodiester linkage on a L-tyrosine residue; major species at pH 7.3.
An alpha-amino-acid residue anion obtained by the addition of 3 AMP residues connected by 3'->5' phosphodiester linkages on a L-tyrosine residue; major species at pH 7.3.
An aldonolactone phosphate that is the 2-phosphate ester of L-ascorbic acid. It can stimulate collagen formation.

An organophosphate oxoanion that is the trianion formed from L-ascorbic acid 2-phosphate by deprotonation of the 3-hydroxy group and of both hydroxy groups of the phosphate function; major species at pH 7.3.
A mineral that is an inorganic nutrient which must be ingested and absorbed in adequate amounts to satisfy a wide range of essential metabolic and/or structural functions in the human body.
Any compound that exhibits antagonist activity at the kappa-opioid receptor.
A ketocholestane that is cholestane which carries an oxo group at position 3.
A 25-hydroxy steroid that is 3-oxocholestane which carries a hydroxy group at position 25.
A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid that is cyclohexane substituted by a hydroxymethyl and carboxymethyl groups at position 1.
A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of hexacyclonic acid, arising from the deprotonation of the carboxy group; Major species at pH 7.3.
A tricarboxylic acid comprising (Z)-but-2-ene having the three carboxy groups at the 1-, 2- and 3-positions.
An aryl sulfate oxoanion resulting from the deprotonation of the sulfooxy group of 2-naphthyl sulfate . The major microspecies at pH 7.3.
A phenyl sulfate oxoanion that is the conjugate base of bisphenol A sulfate, obtained by deprotonation of the sulfo group; major species at pH 7.3.
A member of the class of phenols that is phenol which is carrying an isopropyl group at position 4.
A phenyl sulfate oxoanion that is the conjugate base of 4-isopropylphenyl sulfate, obtained by deprotonation of the sulfate group; major species at pH 7.3.
An alpha-amino-acid residue formed from N-[2-(5-hydroxy-1H-indol-3-yl)ethyl]-L-glutamine.
An alpha-amino-acid residue formed from N-[2-(3,4-dihydroxyphenyl)ethyl]-L-glutamine.

A benzamide resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of 5-amino-2-methylbenzoic acid with the amino group of (1R)-1-(naphthalen-1-yl)ethan-1-amine. It is a potent noncovalent inhibitor (IC50 = 600 nM) of severe acute respiratory syndrome-coronavirus papain-like protease (SARS-CoV PLpro).

A sesterterpenoid that is cyclohexane substituted by methyl, hydroxy, (2E,6E,10E)-1-hydroxy-3,7,11-trimethyltrideca-2,6,10-trien-13-yl, methyl and methyl groups at positions 1,1,2,3 and 3, respectively.
An alpha-amino-acid residue formed from N-[(2R)-2-(3,4-dihydroxyphenyl)-2-hydroxyethyl]-L-glutamine.
An L-alpha-amino acid residue residue derived from N(alpha)-gamma-L-glutamylhistamine
The (S)-enantiomer of reticuline.
An aryl sulfate that is benzene substituted by a propan-2-yl group at position 1 and by a sulfooxy group at position 4.

A pyrazinecarboxamide in which a 6-oxo-1,6-dihydropyrazine nucleus is substituted on C-5 by a 4-hydroxyphenyl group and on C-2 by a butylcarbamyl group. A synthetic determinant of cefadroxil, it is a promising tool for determining in vitro cross-reactivity to cefadroxil in amoxicillin-allergic patients.
A substance which is poisonous to fish and is primarily used to eliminate dominant species of fish in water.

An organic thiophosphate that is O,O-dimethyl O-phenyl phosphorothioate substituted by a chloro group at position 3 and a nitro group at position 4. It is a potent cholinesterase inhibitor and used as an insecticide for the control of a wide range of insects.
A butan-4-olide that is dihydrofuran-2(3H)-one substituted by a hydroxy group at position 3 and two methyl groups at position 4 (the R-stereoisomer).
A primary ammonium ion that is the conjugate acid of dopamine quinone, resulting from the protonation of the primary amino group. Major species at pH 7.3.
